## Single-page applications

Traditional websites work like this: you click a link, the browser requests a new HTML page from the server, the old page disappears, and the new page loads. Every navigation is a full round trip.

React applications work differently. The browser loads ONE HTML page. When you navigate, React swaps out components on that single page to show different content. The URL changes, but the browser never reloads. This is called a **single-page application** (SPA).

This is why React apps feel fast -- navigation is instant because there is no server round trip for each page.

But this raises a question: if there is only one HTML page, how does React know which components to show for each URL? That is where a **router** comes in.

## React Router

The most common routing library for React is **React Router**. It provides components and hooks that match URLs to components. When you see routing code in a React project, it is almost certainly using React Router.

### Route definitions

Routes are defined using `<Route>` components that map URL paths to React components:

```jsx
import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route } from 'react-router-dom';

function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/" element={<HomePage />} />
        <Route path="/about" element={<AboutPage />} />
        <Route path="/products" element={<ProductList />} />
        <Route path="/products/:id" element={<ProductDetail />} />
        <Route path="*" element={<NotFoundPage />} />
      </Routes>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}
```

Reading this:
- When the URL is `/`, show `<HomePage />`
- When the URL is `/about`, show `<AboutPage />`
- When the URL is `/products`, show `<ProductList />`
- When the URL is `/products/42` (or any number), show `<ProductDetail />`
- When the URL is anything else, show `<NotFoundPage />`

The `path` attribute is the URL pattern. The `element` attribute is the component to render.

### Route parameters: the `:id` pattern

When you see a colon in a route path, that is a **route parameter** -- a placeholder for a dynamic value:

```jsx
<Route path="/products/:id" element={<ProductDetail />} />
```

This matches:
- `/products/1`
- `/products/42`
- `/products/abc`

The `:id` part captures whatever is in that position of the URL. The component can then read this value.

### Reading route parameters with useParams

Inside the component, you use the `useParams` hook to read the captured value:

```jsx
function ProductDetail() {
  const { id } = useParams();
  const [product, setProduct] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch(`/api/products/${id}`)
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => setProduct(data));
  }, [id]);

  if (!product) return <Spinner />;

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{product.name}</h1>
      <p>${product.price}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

`useParams()` returns an object with the route parameters. If the URL is `/products/42`, then `id` is `"42"`. Notice how `id` is used in the fetch URL and in the useEffect dependency array -- when the user navigates to a different product, the effect re-runs and fetches the new data.

## Navigation: Link vs. anchor tags

In plain HTML, you navigate with `<a href="/about">About</a>`. In React, using a regular anchor tag causes a full page reload -- which wipes out all your state and defeats the purpose of a single-page app.

React Router provides `<Link>` for navigation without reloading:

```jsx
import { Link } from 'react-router-dom';

function Navbar() {
  return (
    <nav>
      <Link to="/">Home</Link>
      <Link to="/about">About</Link>
      <Link to="/products">Products</Link>
    </nav>
  );
}
```

The key difference:

| `<a href="/about">` | `<Link to="/about">` |
| :-- | :-- |
| Full page reload | No page reload |
| All state is lost | State is preserved |
| Slower (server round trip) | Instant (client-side swap) |
| Standard HTML | React Router |

When you see `<Link>` in code, you know: this navigates without reloading. When you see `<a href>` inside a React app, it might be intentional (linking to an external site) or it might be a bug (should have been a Link).

### When `<a href>` is correct

`<a href>` is still correct for links to external websites or downloadable files:

```jsx
// External link -- <a> is correct
<a href="https://github.com/user/repo">View on GitHub</a>

// Internal navigation -- should use Link
<Link to="/settings">Settings</Link>
```

## Programmatic navigation with useNavigate

Sometimes you need to navigate in response to something other than a click -- after a form submission, after a successful login, or after a timer:

```jsx
import { useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';

function LoginForm() {
  const navigate = useNavigate();
  const [email, setEmail] = useState('');
  const [password, setPassword] = useState('');

  async function handleSubmit(e) {
    e.preventDefault();
    const response = await fetch('/api/login', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify({ email, password }),
    });

    if (response.ok) {
      navigate('/dashboard');  // Redirect to dashboard
    }
  }

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input value={email} onChange={e => setEmail(e.target.value)} />
      <input type="password" value={password} onChange={e => setPassword(e.target.value)} />
      <button type="submit">Log In</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

`useNavigate()` returns a function that you can call to navigate programmatically. `navigate('/dashboard')` changes the URL and renders the component matched by the `/dashboard` route -- all without a page reload.

When you see `useNavigate` in a component, you know it redirects the user somewhere based on logic (not just a link click).

## Nested routes and layouts

Real apps often have a shared layout (header, sidebar) with content that changes based on the route:

```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/" element={<Layout />}>
          <Route index element={<HomePage />} />
          <Route path="settings" element={<SettingsPage />} />
          <Route path="profile" element={<ProfilePage />} />
        </Route>
      </Routes>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}

function Layout() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />
      <Sidebar />
      <main>
        <Outlet />
      </main>
    </div>
  );
}
```

The nested routes mean:
- `Layout` always renders (it has the header and sidebar)
- `<Outlet />` is where the child route's component appears
- At `/`, the Outlet shows `<HomePage />`
- At `/settings`, the Outlet shows `<SettingsPage />`

When you see `<Outlet />` in a component, it is a placeholder that says: "Render the matched child route here."

## Your reading strategy for routing

1. **Find the Route definitions** -- usually in App.jsx or a routes file. This is the map of your app.
2. **Read the paths** -- these are the URLs users can visit.
3. **Read the elements** -- these are the components rendered at each URL.
4. **Look for `:param` patterns** -- these are dynamic segments read with `useParams()`.
5. **Check Link vs. a tags** -- Links navigate without reloading, anchor tags reload.
6. **Check for useNavigate** -- programmatic navigation in response to events.

## Quick reference

| Concept | Code | What it does |
| :-- | :-- | :-- |
| Define a route | `<Route path="/about" element={<About />} />` | Show About component at /about |
| Dynamic route | `<Route path="/users/:id" element={<User />} />` | Capture a URL parameter |
| Read URL param | `const { id } = useParams()` | Access the captured parameter |
| Navigate (link) | `<Link to="/about">` | Navigate without reload |
| Navigate (code) | `navigate('/dashboard')` | Redirect programmatically |
| Catch-all route | `<Route path="*" element={<NotFound />} />` | Handle unknown URLs |
| Layout outlet | `<Outlet />` | Render child route content |

